what i did today

### 1. Display Flex

Converted normal containers into flex containers using `display: flex`
Saw how elements that were stacking vertically started aligning in a row
Understood that Flexbox works on a **parent → child relationship**
Applied it on multiple containers to observe default behavior

---

### 2. Flex Direction

Used `flex-direction` to control the main axis
Tested `row`, `row-reverse`, `column`, `column-reverse`
Observed how direction changes the flow of items
Understood that axis changes everything (alignment behaves differently based on direction)

---

### 3. Justify Content

Aligned items along the **main axis**
Used values: `flex-start`, `flex-end`, `center`, `space-between`, `space-around`, `space-evenly`
Visually compared spacing differences between each value
Understood it controls horizontal alignment in row and vertical in column

---

### 4. Align Items

Aligned items along the **cross axis**
Used values: `stretch`, `flex-start`, `flex-end`, `center`, `baseline`
Observed how height changes when using `stretch`
Learned that it controls vertical alignment in row direction

---

### 5. Align Content

Used on multi-line flex containers
Applied `flex-wrap: wrap` first to activate it
Tested values like `center`, `space-between`, `space-around`
Understood it works only when there are **multiple rows of items**

---

### 6. Flex Wrap

Controlled whether items stay in one line or wrap
Used `nowrap`, `wrap`, `wrap-reverse`
Observed overflow when wrapping was disabled
Saw how items move to the next line when space is insufficient

---

### 7. Gap

Added spacing between flex items using `gap`
Compared it with margin
Understood that gap is cleaner and avoids margin side effects

---

### 8. Flex Grow

Allowed items to grow and take available space
Assigned different grow values to items
Observed proportional expansion
Understood how space is distributed dynamically

---

### 9. Flex Shrink

Controlled how items shrink when space is limited
Tested different shrink values
Saw how some items shrink more than others
Understood its role in responsive layouts

---

### 10. Flex Basis

Defined the initial size of items before grow/shrink
Compared `flex-basis` with width
Observed how it affects layout calculation
Understood it is part of the flex sizing algorithm

---

### 11. Flex Shorthand

Used `flex: grow shrink basis`
Replaced multiple properties with one line
Tested combinations like `flex: 1`, `flex: 2`, `flex: 0 1 auto`
Understood shorthand is commonly used in real projects

---

### 12. Align Self

Overrode alignment for individual items
Applied different values on single items
Saw how one item behaves differently from others
Understood it overrides `align-items`

---

### 13. Order

Changed visual order of items without changing HTML
Assigned different order values
Observed rearrangement in layout
Understood it only affects visual order, not DOM structure

---

## Key Observations From Practical

Flexbox is one-dimensional — it works either in row or column
Main axis vs cross axis understanding is the core of Flexbox
`justify-content` and `align-items` depend on direction
Flexbox removes the need for floats and manual spacing hacks
`gap` is cleaner than using margins for spacing
Flex properties (`grow`, `shrink`, `basis`) control responsive behavior
Flexbox is best for aligning and distributing space in components

---

## Mistakes I Made During Practical

Used `align-content` without enabling wrapping — no effect was visible
Confused main axis and cross axis — alignment looked incorrect
Used margin instead of gap — spacing became inconsistent
Set fixed width on items — flex-grow was not working properly
Expected `order` to change HTML structure

---

## How I Fixed Them

Enabled `flex-wrap: wrap` before using `align-content`
Clearly identified main axis using `flex-direction`
Replaced margin spacing with `gap`
Removed fixed widths to allow flexible sizing
Understood `order` only changes visual position, not DOM

---

## Reflection

Flexbox made layout control feel structured and predictable. The biggest shift was understanding **axis-based thinking** — once the main axis is clear, everything else becomes logical. Seeing how items expand, shrink, and align dynamically made it clear why Flexbox is heavily used in modern UI design. It removes the need for hacks and makes responsive layouts much easier to build.
